A1YfuCcPdVI.title: 60 Minute Slow Flow Power Yoga
A1YfuCcPdVI.description:
This is a sixty minute free yoga class - it's a slow flow power yoga practice. It's not appropriate for total beginners (i.e. people with less than ten classes under their belts) but anyone else should be okay with this, provided they take the modifications needed and understand that it is a power class - you will be sweating and working quite hard! As always, listen to your body and take a break when needed in child's pose or savasana. 

In this class we stretch, then work into a vinyasa flow, practice balances like warrior three and crow pose, and play around with baby grasshopper. It's a challenging yoga class, but enjoyable! I hope you love it!

OzSKtpX9Q1E.title: How to use a yoga/stretching strap
OzSKtpX9Q1E.description:
How to use a yoga/stretching strap

Alright, so you are looking to increase your flexibility with yoga/stretching strap? This video will show you how to use yoga strap for stretching, how to build flexibility and achieve better balance and form in yoga poses.

Props used in this video:

Yoga strap by FitlifestyleCo - check it out at Amazon, click this Amazon
link:
http://www.amazon.com/Best-Yoga-Strap-FitLifestyleCo-Stretching/dp/B00X7N1MRW/ref=aag_m_pw_dp?ie=UTF8&m=A2XKRHQGPAKUO8
Yoga mat with integrated towel by FitLifestyleCo - check it out at
Amazon, click this Amazon link:
http://www.amazon.com/Best-Yoga-With-Integrated-Towel/dp/B00WRA2HVQ/ref=aag_m_pw_dp?ie=UTF8&m=A2XKRHQGPAKUO8

Introduction

Why to use the yoga strap? Some people stay away from trying yoga cause they think they are not flexible enough. That is where using yoga strap comes handy, you can gain these benefits:
- Improved flexibility
- Better balance and form in yoga poses
- Increased strength and endurance
- Stretching will get easier, gradually you can build up flexibility by
moving your arms further on the strap
- Straps are enabling you to grasp limbs that are otherwise too far
away. For example if you cannot touch your toes, the strap/belt will
help you to bridge that gap.

How to use a yoga strap in seated poses

In seated postures like the hamstring stretch, yoga straps can be used
around the feet as shown. Arms should be straight, and grab hold
wherever you can. The pelvis will naturally tilt forward, bringing the
body into alignment and bringing length into the hamstrings. It isn't
often that we sit like this, so shoulders might creep up toward the ears with tension. Be mindful of that, and relax the shoulders away from the ears, keeping the spine long and the shoulder blades melting down the back. Sternum is lifted.

How to use a yoga strap in balancing poses

For balancing postures, the strap can be used in poses like extended
hand to big toe when the flexibility isn't as developed. Loop the strap
around the foot as shown, and grab hold as close to the foot as you can, keeping the body long and in alignment, and keeping the arm straight. Activate the entire leg and breathe.

For more detailed info about "How to use a yoga strap in binds", "How to use a yoga strap for shoulders", "How to use a yoga strap in arm
balances" please visit our blog post here:
http://yogabycandace.com/blog/2013/11/5/how-to-use-a-yoga-strap

Qpcet63mXKs.title: 15 Minute Hip Opening Yoga Practice with a Bench
Qpcet63mXKs.description:
This is a 15 minute hip opening yoga practice with a Bhoga bench. Hip opening is excellent for relieving tension, and may actually improve back pain and posture issues. The use of the bench is especially helpful for people with limited flexibility and who are relatively new to yoga. You'll see poses like downward facing dog, pigeon pose, and more in this sequence to help loosen tight muscles and improve flexibility. Hope you enjoy!

2-tp-8gG9Bs.title: Ask a Yoga Question - EPISODE 4
2-tp-8gG9Bs.description:
Ask a Yoga Question is a weekly series on www.YogaByCandace.com where I answer readers' questions. This week's questions: 
Q1, :08 - I have recently been diagnosed with carpel tunnel syndrome and plank pose, chaturanga, downward dog, etc cause a lot of pain. What can I do?
Q2: Do you have any tips for drop backs? I get really nervous when doing them.
Q3: I've been focusing on wild thing. I was wondering if you have any recommendations on the best ways in and out of the pose? Any prep poses?
Q4: I am progressing well in arm balances, but dragonfly completely evades me. I can't seem to get my foot about my elbow and don't know what to do. Any tips?

Links for prep poses for wild thing pose:
1. Downward dog: http://yogabycandace.com/blog/yoga-for-men-down-dog-yoga-crow-review
2. Side plank: http://yogabycandace.com/blog/2014/2/11/how-to-do-side-plank-pose
3. Extended side angle pose: http://yogabycandace.com/blog/2013/5/31/tips-for-parsvakonasana

Please subscribe to the YouTube channel so you don’t miss out on our weekly yoga classes!

zcWWa0jjViA.title: Ask a Yoga Question - Episode 3
zcWWa0jjViA.description:
Ask a yoga question is a series on my blog, www.yogabycandace.com, where I answer reader yoga questions.

Q1, :19: I just started yoga a few months ago with your videos. They are great, but I think I have done something wrong as I have pain in both shoulders. My self diagnosis says it may be pulled bicep tendons, maybe due to poor chaturanga form. Have you heard of this and do you have suggestions on 1) how to heal, or 2) what I can do in the meantime?

Answer, :40.

Q2, 2:33: I want to do crow pose and headstand but I am afraid of falling and cracking my neck. How did you overcome this fear and what do you suggest I do? 

Answer, 2:42.

Q3. 4:21: I've practiced yoga for ten years more or less regularly. I started yoga teacher training and in class we did a partner exercise for handstands. we had a partner supporting us while we tried to go into full handstand. It was very hard for me though someone was holding my legs and there for me. I don't know why I was not able to do this exercise the way it should've been done. Do I need to build up more arm strength or is it my core I have to work on? Any advice for me to work on headstand? 

Answer, 4:50.

ZTbF0hSXQXE.title: 20 Minute Yoga Flow for Core Strengthening
ZTbF0hSXQXE.description:
This is an instructional 20 minute yoga video that aims to strengthen the core in preparation for arm balances such as crow pose, headstand, handstand and forearm stand. The intention is to work all parts of the core including the upper abs, lower abs and obliques in a variety of ways that keeps the body guessing. 

In this flow, we also practice a few arm balances including baby grasshopper pose. It goes a little fast in this flow so if you need more instruction please check out this link: http://yogabycandace.com/blog/how-to-do-baby-grasshopper-pose

VGC8EzZqH7M.title: 10 Min Chair Yoga for the Office
VGC8EzZqH7M.description:
Take a 10 min yoga break at the office with this gentle yoga sequence. It's a great way to loosen up the hips, low back, upper back, arms, shoulders, and neck. Remember to breathe deeply. Also, we're using a chair for this yoga practice. Any chair will do, though one without an armrest is preferred.

This week's questions: 
:20 Q1: Can you give tips for getting into fish pose? 
2:05 Q2: What sort of poses can I start incorporating to improve my practice and take it to the next level?
4:46 Q3: What other poses can I do to help my legs relax and straighten in downward facing dog?

Kxxx9hPeNVk.title: YogaByCandace Sweat DVD Trailer
Kxxx9hPeNVk.description:
An overview of what to expect when you order the Sweat DVD from yogabycandace.com. It's a 60 minute power vinyasa sequence that begins with a centering, moves to gentle poses to warm up the body, begins a challenging vinyasa sequence followed by a standing a balancing series. After that we come to the mat for seated poses and core strengthening, and then come all the way down for supine positions and end in savasana. Place our order now at yogabycandace.com.

l8RAPpmUc70.title: Drop backs
l8RAPpmUc70.description: Practicing drop backs. Start standing tall, engage the quads. Lengthen up from all four corners of both feet through the crown of the head. Inhale and lift the arms. Engage the abs, feeling yourself lift and lengthen as you go back gently and with control.

localized.title: Drop backs
localized.description: Practicing drop backs. Start standing tall, engage the quads. Lengthen up from all four corners of both feet through the crown of the head. Inhale and lift the arms. Engage the abs, feeling yourself lift and lengthen as you go back gently and with control.
